{"title": "Disregard That Statement", "content": "Vinny: Uh... Everything that guy just said is bullshit... Thank you.\n\nA kind of Courtroom Antic where the lawyer asks or says something totally inappropriate to the rules of the courtroom in order to get the jury to think of something a certain way. A classic example is, \"Have you stopped beating your wife yet?\"\n\nNaturally, the opposing lawyer will object, and then the Judge will say, without fail; \"The members of the jury are instructed to disregard that statement.\" Original lawyer smirks because apparently only he realizes that people cannot voluntarily self-induce amnesia through sheer willpower* and we're talking amnesia in general, never mind the laser-guided kind. If he's really being smug, he'll withdraw the statement himself before the other lawyer can finish objecting.\n\nIn the real world, this is a good way to lose the right to practice law; never mind using it as a common tactic. Lawyers refer to this method as \"ringing the bell\", because you can't un-ring a bell.\n\nWhen the opposing counsel attempts to invoke this trope without a proper reason, it's That Was Objectionable.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DisregardThatStatement", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MyCousinVinny", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AnatomyOfAMurder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Chicago", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheExorcismOfEmilyRose", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MyCousinVinny", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ATimeToKill", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AndJusticeForAll", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/LiarLiar", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IntolerableCruelty", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/SnowFallingOnCedars", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheVerdict", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/AFewGoodMen", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Shark", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheWire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/LawAndOrder", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/BostonLegal", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/JAG", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Bones", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php